{"id":"1610.04635","submitter":"Rogelio Caballero-Lopez","authors":"H. Moraal, R. A. Caballero-Lopez, and K. G. McCracken","title":"The cosmic-ray ground-level enhancements of 29 September 1989 and 20\n  January 2005","comments":"Proc. 34rd International Cosmic Ray Conference, 2015","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"physics.space-ph astro-ph.SR","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Enhancements of the comic-ray intensity as observed by detectors on the\nground have been observed 71 times since 1942. They are due to solar energetic\nparticles accelerated in the regions of solar flares deep in the corona, or in\nthe shock front of coronal mass ejections (CMEs) in the solar wind. The latter\nis the favoured model for the classical gradual ground level enhancement (GLE).\nIn several papers since the one of McCracken et al. (2008), we pointed out,\nhowever, that some GLEs are too impulsive to be accelerated in the CME shocks.\nThis hypothesis, together with other properties of GLEs, is demonstrated\ngraphically in this paper by plotting and comparing the time profiles of GLEs\n42 of 29 September 1989 and GLE 69 of 20 January. These two events are\nrespectively the largest examples of gradual and prompt events.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 26 Apr 2016 03:24:32 GMT"}],"update_date":"2016-10-18"}
